# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/alexey-favorsky] Favorsky studied chemistry at the imperial Saint Petersburg State University from 1878 to 1882.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/alexey-favorsky] He joined Alexander Butlerov's laboratory for several years, and in 1891 became a lecturer.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/alexey-favorsky] In 1895, Favorksy received his PhD and became professor for technical chemistry.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/alexey-favorsky] His discovery of the Favorskii rearrangement in 1894 and the Favorskii reaction between 1900 and 1905 are connected to his name.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/alexey-favorsky] He worked at the new organics department from 1897, and served as its director from 1934 to 1937.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/alexey-favorsky] For his improvement of the production of synthetic rubber, Favorsky was awarded the Stalin Prize in 1941.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/alexey-favorsky] The artist Vladimir Favorsky was his nephew.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/alexey-favorsky] Favorsky died in 1945 and was buried at the Volkovskoye Orthodox cemetery.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/boris-nikolsky] Besides his work on the plutonium chemistry, Nikolsky did a pioneering work in ion exchanges applications in radiochemistry and physical chemistry, and was a professor of chemistry at the Leningrad University (now Saint Petersburg State University).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/boris-nikolsky] He academician of the Soviet Academy of Sciences.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/boris-nikolsky] Boris Nikolsky was a 1925 graduate of Leningrad State University.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/boris-nikolsky] In the 1930s he studied the ion exchange processes between aqueous solutions and solids.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/boris-nikolsky] During that time Nikolsky developed the theory of ion exchange in glass electrodes.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/boris-nikolsky] Boris Nikolsky also actively participated in the Soviet nuclear program.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/boris-nikolsky] In 1952-1974 he was the senior scientist and the chairman of scientific committee at the Soviet nuclear fuel reprocessing plant Mayak, where he worked on the technology of processing and refining of plutonium.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/boris-nikolsky] In 1961-1963 he was the chairman of the chemistry department at Leningrad State University.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/boris-nikolsky] Boris Nikolsky was a co-author of the monumental textbook on physical chemistry and an editor-in-chief of the most comprehensive multivolume handbook of chemistry in Soviet Union.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev was born in the village of Verkhnie Aremzyani, near Tobolsk in Siberia, to Ivan Pavlovich Mendeleev (1783–1847) and Maria Dmitrievna Mendeleeva (née Kornilieva) (1793–1850).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Ivan worked as a school principal and a teacher of fine arts, politics and philosophy at the Tambov and Saratov gymnasiums.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Ivan's father, Pavel Maximovich Sokolov, was a Russian Orthodox priest from the Tver region.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] As per the tradition of priests of that time, Pavel's children were given new family names while attending the theological seminary, with Ivan getting the family name Mendeleev after the name of a local landlord.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Maria Kornilieva came from a well-known family of Tobolsk merchants, founders of the first Siberian printing house who traced their ancestry to Yakov Korniliev, a 17th-century posad man turned a wealthy merchant.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1889, a local librarian published an article in the Tobolsk newspaper where he claimed that Yakov was a baptized Teleut, an ethnic minority known as "white Kalmyks" at the time.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Since no sources were provided and no documented facts of Yakov's life were ever revealed, biographers generally dismiss it as a myth.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1908, shortly after Mendeleev's death, one of his nieces published *Family Chronicles.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev* where she voiced "a family legend" about Maria's grandfather who married "a Kyrgyz or Tatar beauty whom he loved so much that when she died, he also died from grief".
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] This, however, contradicts the documented family chronicles, and neither of those legends is supported by Mendeleev's autobiography, his daughter's or his wife's memoirs.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Yet some Western scholars still refer to Mendeleev's supposed "Mongol", "Tatar", "Tartarian" or simply "Asian" ancestry as a fact.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev was raised as an Orthodox Christian, his mother encouraging him to "patiently search divine and scientific truth".
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] His son Ivan would later inform that Mendeleev had departed from the Church and embraced a form of "romanticized deism".
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev was the youngest of 17 siblings, of whom "only 14 stayed alive to be baptized" according to Mendeleev's brother Pavel, meaning the others died soon after their birth.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The exact number of Mendeleev's siblings differs among sources and is still a matter of some historical dispute.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Unfortunately for the family's financial well-being, his father became blind and lost his teaching position.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] His mother was forced to work and she restarted her family's abandoned glass factory.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] At the age of 13, after the death of his father and the destruction of his mother's factory by fire, Mendeleev attended the Gymnasium in Tobolsk.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1849, his mother took Mendeleev across Russia from Siberia to Moscow with the aim of getting Mendeleev enrolled at the Moscow University.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The university in Moscow did not accept him.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The mother and son continued to Saint Petersburg to the father's alma mater.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The now poor Mendeleev family relocated to Saint Petersburg, where he entered the Main Pedagogical Institute in 1850.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] After graduation, he contracted tuberculosis, causing him to move to the Crimean Peninsula on the northern coast of the Black Sea in 1855.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] While there, he became a science master of the 1st Simferopol Gymnasium.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1857, he returned to Saint Petersburg with fully restored health.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Between 1859 and 1861, he worked on the capillarity of liquids and the workings of the spectroscope in Heidelberg.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Later in 1861, he published a textbook named *Organic Chemistry*.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] This won him the Demidov Prize of the Petersburg Academy of Sciences.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] On 4 April 1862, he became engaged to Feozva Nikitichna Leshcheva, and they married on 27 April 1862 at Nikolaev Engineering Institute's church in Saint Petersburg (where he taught).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev became a professor at the Saint Petersburg Technological Institute and Saint Petersburg State University in 1864, and 1865, respectively.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1865, he became a Doctor of Science for his dissertation "On the Combinations of Water with Alcohol".
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Petersburg University and started to teach inorganic chemistry while succeeding Voskresenskii to this post; by 1871, he had transformed Saint Petersburg into an internationally recognized center for chemistry research.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1863, there were 56 known elements, with a new element being discovered at a rate of approximately one per year.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Other scientists had previously identified periodicity of elements.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] John Newlands described a Law of Octaves, noting their periodicity according to relative atomic weight in 1864, publishing it in 1865.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] His proposal identified the potential for new elements such as germanium.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The concept was criticized, and his innovation was not recognized by the Society of Chemists until 1887.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Another person to propose a periodic table was Lothar Meyer, who published a paper in 1864 describing 28 elements classified by their valence, but with no predictions of new elements.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] After becoming a teacher in 1867, Mendeleev wrote *Principles of Chemistry* (Russian: Основы химии, romanized: *Osnovy khimii*), which became the definitive textbook of its time.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] It was published in two volumes between 1868 and 1870, and Mendeleev wrote it as he was preparing a textbook for his course.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] This is when he made his most important discovery.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] By adding additional elements following this pattern, Mendeleev developed his extended version of the periodic table.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] On 6 March 1869, he made a formal presentation to the Russian Chemical Society, titled *The Dependence between the Properties of the Atomic Weights of the Elements*, which described elements according to both atomic weight (now called *relative atomic mass*) and valence.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Elements which are similar regarding their chemical properties either have similar atomic weights (e.g., Pt, Ir, Os) or have their atomic weights increasing regularly (e.g., K, Rb, Cs).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The arrangement of the elements in groups of elements in the order of their atomic weights corresponds to their so-called valencies, as well as, to some extent, to their distinctive chemical properties; as is apparent among other series in that of Li, Be, B, C, N, O, and F.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The elements which are the most widely diffused have small atomic weights.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The magnitude of the atomic weight determines the character of the element, just as the magnitude of the molecule determines the character of a compound body.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] We must expect the discovery of many yet unknown elements – for example, two elements, analogous to aluminium and silicon, whose atomic weights would be between 65 and 75.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The atomic weight of an element may sometimes be amended by a knowledge of those of its contiguous elements.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Thus the atomic weight of tellurium must lie between 123 and 126, and cannot be 128.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Certain characteristic properties of elements can be foretold from their atomic weights.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev published his periodic table of all known elements and predicted several new elements to complete the table in a Russian-language journal.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Only a few months after, Meyer published a virtually identical table in a German-language journal.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev has the distinction of accurately predicting the properties of what he called ekasilicon, ekaaluminium and ekaboron (germanium, gallium and scandium, respectively).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev also proposed changes in the properties of some known elements.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Prior to his work, uranium was supposed to have valence 3 and atomic weight about 120.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev realized that these values did not fit in his periodic table, and doubled both to valence 6 and atomic weight 240 (close to the modern value of 238).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] For his predicted three elements, he used the prefixes of eka, dvi, and tri (Sanskrit one, two, three) in their naming.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev questioned some of the currently accepted atomic weights (they could be measured only with a relatively low accuracy at that time), pointing out that they did not correspond to those suggested by his Periodic Law.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He noted that tellurium has a higher atomic weight than iodine, but he placed them in the right order, incorrectly predicting that the accepted atomic weights at the time were at fault.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He was puzzled about where to put the known lanthanides, and predicted the existence of another row to the table which were the actinides which were some of the heaviest in atomic weight.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Some people dismissed Mendeleev for predicting that there would be more elements, but he was proven to be correct when Ga (gallium) and Ge (germanium) were found in 1875 and 1886 respectively, fitting perfectly into the two missing spaces.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev was a friend and colleague of the Sanskritist Otto von Böhtlingk, who was preparing the second edition of his book on Pāṇini at about this time, and Mendeleev wished to honor Pāṇini with his nomenclature.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Dmitri Mendeleev is often referred to as the Father of the Periodic Table.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He called his table or matrix, "the Periodic System".
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1876, he met Anna Ivanovna Popova and began courting her; in 1881 he proposed to her and threatened suicide if she refused.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] His divorce from Leshcheva was finalized one month after he had married Popova (on 2 April) in early 1882.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Even after the divorce, Mendeleev was technically a bigamist; the Russian Orthodox Church required at least seven years before lawful remarriage.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] His divorce and the surrounding controversy contributed to his failure to be admitted to the Russian Academy of Sciences (despite his international fame by that time).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] His daughter from his second marriage, Lyubov, became the wife of the famous Russian poet Alexander Blok.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] His other children were son Vladimir (a sailor, he took part in the notable Eastern journey of Nicholas II) and daughter Olga, from his first marriage to Feozva, and son Ivan and twins from Anna.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Though Mendeleev was widely honored by scientific organizations all over Europe, including (in 1882) the Davy Medal from the Royal Society of London (which later also awarded him the Copley Medal in 1905), he resigned from Saint Petersburg University on 17 August 1890.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society (ForMemRS) in 1892, and in 1893 he was appointed director of the Bureau of Weights and Measures, a post which he occupied until his death.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev also investigated the composition of petroleum, and helped to found the first oil refinery in Russia.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He recognized the importance of petroleum as a feedstock for petrochemicals.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He is credited with a remark that burning petroleum as a fuel "would be akin to firing up a kitchen stove with bank notes".
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev was nominated for Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the last three years of his life, 1905, 1906 and 1907 in 9 nominations.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1905, Mendeleev was elected a member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences and received three nominations.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The following year he received four nominations and the Nobel Committee for Chemistry recommended to the Swedish Academy to award the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for 1906 to Mendeleev for his discovery of the periodic system.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He was also elected an International Member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The Chemistry Section of the Swedish Academy supported this recommendation.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The academy was then supposed to approve the committee's choice, as it has done in almost every case.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Unexpectedly, at the full meeting of the academy, a dissenting member of the Nobel Committee, Peter Klason, proposed the candidacy of Henri Moissan whom he favored.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Svante Arrhenius, although not a member of the Nobel Committee for Chemistry, had a great deal of influence in the academy and also pressed for the rejection of Mendeleev, arguing that the periodic system was too old to acknowledge its discovery in 1906.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] According to the contemporaries, Arrhenius was motivated by the grudge he held against Mendeleev for his critique of Arrhenius's dissociation theory.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] After heated arguments, the majority of the academy chose Moissan by a margin of one vote.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The two nominations of Mendeleev in 1907 were again frustrated by the absolute opposition of Arrhenius.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1907, Mendeleev died at the age of 72 in Saint Petersburg from influenza.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] His last words were to his physician: "Doctor, you have science, I have faith," which is possibly a Jules Verne quote.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He was buried at Literatorskie Mostki cementary.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev made other important contributions to science.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev was one of the founders, in 1868, of the Russian Chemical Society.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He worked on the theory and practice of protectionist trade and on agriculture.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In an attempt at a chemical conception of the aether, he put forward a hypothesis that there existed two inert chemical elements of lesser atomic weight than hydrogen.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Of these two proposed elements, he thought the lighter to be an all-penetrating, all-pervasive gas, and the slightly heavier one to be a proposed element, *coronium*.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev devoted much study and made important contributions to the determination of the nature of such indefinite compounds as solutions.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev is given credit for the introduction of the metric system to the Russian Empire.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He invented *pyrocollodion*, a kind of smokeless powder based on nitrocellulose.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] This work had been commissioned by the Russian Navy, which however did not adopt its use.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1892 Mendeleev organized its manufacture.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev studied the origins of petroleum; he concluded that hydrocarbons are abiogenic and form deep within the earth – see Abiogenic petroleum origin.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Beginning in the 1870s, he published widely beyond chemistry, looking at aspects of Russian industry, and technical issues in agricultural productivity.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He explored demographic issues, sponsored studies of the Arctic Sea, tried to measure the efficacy of chemical fertilizers, and promoted the merchant navy.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He was especially active in improving the Russian petroleum industry, making detailed comparisons with the more advanced industry in Pennsylvania.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Although not well-grounded in economics, he had observed industry throughout his European travels, and in 1891 he helped convince the Ministry of Finance to impose temporary tariffs with the aim of fostering Russian infant industries.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1889, he was elected as an honorary member of the Manchester Literary and Philosophical Society.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The following year, 1890, he resigned his professorship at St.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Petersburg University following a dispute with officials at the Ministry of Education over the treatment of university students.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In 1892 he was appointed director of Russia's Central Bureau of Weights and Measures, and led the way to standardize fundamental prototypes and measurement procedures.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He set up an inspection system, and introduced the metric system to Russia.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He debated against the scientific claims of spiritualism, arguing that metaphysical idealism was no more than ignorant superstition.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] He bemoaned the widespread acceptance of spiritualism in Russian culture, and its negative effects on the study of science.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] A very popular Russian story credits Mendeleev with setting the 40% standard strength of vodka.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In fact, the 40% standard had already been introduced by the Russian government in 1843, when Mendeleev was nine years old.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Also, Mendeleev's 1865 doctoral dissertation was entitled "A Discourse on the combination of alcohol and water", but it only discussed medical-strength alcohol concentrations over 70%, and he never wrote anything about vodka.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] A number of places and objects are associated with the name and achievements of the scientist.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In Saint Petersburg his name was given to D.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleev Institute for Metrology, the National Metrology Institute, dealing with establishing and supporting national and worldwide standards for precise measurements.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Next to it there is a monument to him that consists of his sitting statue and a depiction of his periodic table on the wall of the establishment.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] In the Twelve Collegia building, now being the centre of Saint Petersburg State University and in Mendeleev's time – Head Pedagogical Institute – there is Dmitry Mendeleev's Memorial Museum Apartment with his archives.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The street in front of these is named after him as Mendeleevskaya liniya (Mendeleev Line).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendeleyev University of Chemical Technology of Russia.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] Mendelevium, which is a synthetic chemical element with the symbol Md (formerly Mv) and the atomic number 101, was named after Mendeleev.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] It is a metallic radioactive transuranic element in the actinide series, usually synthesized by bombarding einsteinium with alpha particles.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The mineral mendeleevite-Ce, Cs 6(Ce 22Ca 6)(Si 70O 175)(OH,F) 14(H 2O) 21, was named in Mendeleev's honor in 2010.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] A large lunar impact crater Mendeleev, that is located on the far side of the Moon, also bears the name of the scientist.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] The Russian Academy of Sciences has occasionally awarded a Mendeleev Golden Medal since 1965.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/dmitri-mendeleev] On 8 February 2016, Mendeleev's 182nd birthday was celebrated with a Google doodle.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] A **geographic coordinate system** (**GCS**) is a spherical or geodetic coordinate system for measuring and communicating positions directly on Earth as latitude and longitude.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] It is the simplest, oldest, and most widely used type of the various spatial reference systems that are in use, and forms the basis for most others.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Although latitude and longitude form a coordinate tuple like a Cartesian coordinate system, geographic coordinate systems are not Cartesian because the measurements are angles and are not on a planar surface.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] A full GCS specification, such as those listed in the EPSG and ISO 19111 standards, also includes a choice of geodetic datum (including an Earth ellipsoid), as different datums will yield different latitude and longitude values for the same location.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The invention of a geographic coordinate system is generally credited to Eratosthenes of Cyrene, who composed his now-lost *Geography* at the Library of Alexandria in the 3rd century BC.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] A century later, Hipparchus of Nicaea improved on this system by determining latitude from stellar measurements rather than solar altitude and determining longitude by timings of lunar eclipses, rather than dead reckoning.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy credited him with the full adoption of longitude and latitude, rather than measuring latitude in terms of the length of the midsummer day.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy's 2nd-century *Geography* used the same prime meridian but measured latitude from the Equator instead.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] After their work was translated into Arabic in the 9th century, Al-Khwārizmī's *Book of the Description of the Earth* corrected Marinus' and Ptolemy's errors regarding the length of the Mediterranean Sea, causing medieval Arabic cartography to use a prime meridian around 10° east of Ptolemy's line.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Mathematical cartography resumed in Europe following Maximus Planudes' recovery of Ptolemy's text a little before 1300; the text was translated into Latin at Florence by Jacopo d'Angelo around 1407.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] In 1884, the United States hosted the International Meridian Conference, attended by representatives from twenty-five nations.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Twenty-two of them agreed to adopt the longitude of the Royal Observatory in Greenwich, England as the zero-reference line.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The Dominican Republic voted against the motion, while France and Brazil abstained.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] France adopted Greenwich Mean Time in place of local determinations by the Paris Observatory in 1911.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The *latitude* φ of a point on Earth's surface is defined in one of three ways, depending on the type of coordinate system.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] In each case, the latitude is the angle formed by the plane of the equator and a line formed by the point on the surface and a second point on equatorial plane.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The path that joins all points of the same latitude traces a circle on the surface of Earth, as viewed from above the north or south pole, called parallels, as they are parallel to the equator and to each other.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The north pole is 90° N; the south pole is 90° S.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The 0° parallel of latitude is defined to be the equator, the fundamental plane of a geographic coordinate system.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The equator divides the globe into Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The *longitude* λ of a point on Earth's surface is the angle east or west of a reference meridian to another meridian that passes through that point.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] All meridians are halves of great ellipses, which converge at the North and South Poles.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The meridian of the British Royal Observatory in Greenwich, in southeast London, England, is the international prime meridian, although some organizations—such as the French Institut national de l'information géographique et forestière—continue to use other meridians for internal purposes.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The antipodal meridian of Greenwich is both 180°W and 180°E.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] This is not to be conflated with the International Date Line, which partly overlaps with the 180° meridian but diverges from it in several places for political and convenience reasons, including between far eastern Russia and the far western Aleutian Islands.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The combination of these two components specifies the position of any location on the surface of Earth, without consideration of altitude or depth.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The visual grid on a map formed by lines of latitude and longitude is known as a *graticule*.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The origin/zero point of this system is located in the Gulf of Guinea about 625 km (390 mi) south of Tema, Ghana, a location often facetiously called Null Island.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] In order to use the theoretical definitions of latitude, longitude, and height to precisely measure actual locations on the physical earth, a *geodetic datum* must be used.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] A *horizonal datum* is used to precisely measure latitude and longitude, while a *vertical datum* is used to measure elevation or altitude.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Both types of datum bind a mathematical model of the shape of the earth (usually a reference ellipsoid for a horizontal datum, and a more precise geoid for a vertical datum) to the earth.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Traditionally, this binding was created by a network of control points, surveyed locations at which monuments are installed, and were only accurate for a region of the surface of the Earth.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Newer datums are based on a global network for satellite measurements (GNSS, VLBI, SLR and DORIS).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] This combination of a mathematical model and physical binding ensures that users of the same datum obtain identical coordinates for a given physical point.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] However, different datums typically produce different coordinates for the same location (sometimes deviating several hundred meters) not due to actual movement, but because the reference system itself is shifted.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Because any spatial reference system or map projection is ultimately calculated from latitude and longitude, it is crucial that they clearly state the datum on which they are based.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] For example, a UTM coordinate based on a WGS84 realisation will be different than a UTM coordinate based on NAD27 for the same location.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Transforming coordinates from one datum to another requires a datum transformation method such as a Helmert transformation, although in certain situations a simple translation may be sufficient.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums may be global, meaning that they represent the whole Earth, or they may be regional, meaning that they represent an ellipsoid best-fit to only a portion of the Earth.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums with a regional fit of the ellipsoid that are chosen by a national cartographical organization include the North American Datums, the European ED50, and the British OSGB36.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Given a location, the datum provides the latitude $\phi$ and longitude $\lambda$ .
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] In the United Kingdom there are three common latitude, longitude, and height systems in use.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] WGS 84 differs at Greenwich from the one used on published maps OSGB36 by approximately 112 m.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Points on the Earth's surface move relative to each other due to continental plate motion, subsidence, and diurnal Earth tidal movement caused by the Moon and the Sun.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] This daily movement can be as much as a meter.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Continental movement can be up to 10 cm a year, or 10 m in a century.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] A weather system high-pressure area can cause a sinking of 5 mm.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Scandinavia is rising by 1 cm a year as a result of the melting of the ice sheets of the last ice age, but neighboring Scotland is rising by only 0.2 cm.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] These changes are insignificant if a regional datum is used, but are statistically significant if a global datum is used.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] On the GRS 80 or WGS 84 spheroid at sea level at the Equator, one latitudinal second measures 30.715 m, one latitudinal minute is 1843 m and one latitudinal degree is 110.6 km.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The circles of longitude, meridians, meet at the geographical poles, with the west–east width of a second naturally decreasing as latitude increases.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] On the Equator at sea level, one longitudinal second measures 30.92 m, a longitudinal minute is 1855 m and a longitudinal degree is 111.3 km.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The returned measure of meters per degree latitude varies continuously with latitude.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] The formulae both return units of meters per degree.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] ( $\textstyle {\beta }\,\!$ is known as the reduced (or parametric) latitude).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Aside from rounding, this is the exact distance along a parallel of latitude; getting the distance along the shortest route will be more work, but those two distances are always within 0.6 m of each other if the two points are one degree of longitude apart.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] Like any series of multiple-digit numbers, latitude-longitude pairs can be challenging to communicate and remember.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/geographic-coordinate-system] These are not distinct coordinate systems, only alternative methods for expressing latitude and longitude measurements.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/lev-aleksandrovich-chugaev] Chugaev discovered that dimethylglyoxime forms a scarlet solid upon reaction with nickel(II) ions.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/lev-aleksandrovich-chugaev] This reaction was one of the first "spot tests" for a metal ion.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/lev-aleksandrovich-chugaev] An adherent to the theories of Alfred Werner, Chugaev made several contributions to the chemistry of platinum.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/lev-aleksandrovich-chugaev] The salt [Pt(NH3)5Cl]Cl3 containing the chloropentammineplatinum(IV) ion, is called "Chugaev's salt".
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/lev-aleksandrovich-chugaev] Other complexes prepared in his laboratory include [Pt(SEt2)4][PtCl4], [Pt(NH3)5OH]Cl3, [Os(SC(NH2)2)6]Cl3.H2O.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/lev-aleksandrovich-chugaev] Chugaev also studied complexes of hydrazine.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/lev-aleksandrovich-chugaev] One of his complexes, since also called Chugaev's salt, was the product of the reaction of platinum(II) salts with methyl isocyanide and hydrazine.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/lev-aleksandrovich-chugaev] After many decades, this compound was shown to be a carbene complex, probably the first metal carbene complex ever reported.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/lev-aleksandrovich-chugaev] He discovered the Chugaev reaction during his work on thujene and terpene.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] In Russia and throughout the world, Shultz is primarily known for his research into chemical thermodynamics of heterogeneous chemical compounds, electrochemistry of glasses, and membrane electrochemistry.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] He is also known for his work in the field of ion exchange and phase equilibria of multicomponent compounds, and theory of glass electrode.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Shultz also worked on a thermal protection system for the Soviet Buran spacecraft and is credited with research in optical fibres in the 1980s.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] His works helped to contribute to the creation of early pH-meters and ionometry, production organisation, instrumentation and materials commonly used in medicine, chemical and nuclear industry, aviation rocket and space technology, agriculture and many other areas.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Mikhail Shultz was a son of Mikhail Alexandrovich Shultz (1896–1954; the Naval officer, belonging to the latest issue of the Imperial Naval Cadet Corps — 1916) and a great-grandson of the Russian physicist Dmitry Aleksandrovich Lachinov (1842–1902).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Shultz was a descendant of the German sculptor, the Danish royal medallist Anton Schultz (Anton Schultz — Schleswig-Holstein, Saxony, Hamburg, Denmark, XVII–XVIII cc.) who carried out orders the Russian Court as early as Copenhagen, and arrived at the service in Russia with Peter the Great.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] He was born on 1 July 1919 in Petrograd, in 1937—graduated with honours from high school (Staraya Russa; where he deported with his mother Helen (née Barsukova) in 1929, his father M.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Shultz was arrested in 1925 as a suspect in the "counter-revolutionary monarchist conspiracy"; he spent 10 years in Solovki prison camp, and 3 years on the construction of the Moscow Canal. released in 1937, rehabilitated in 1991).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] 1937–1941—a student of the chemical faculty of the Leningrad State University (M.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Mendeleev, in 1941–1945—a volunteer on The Great Patriotic War, first lieutenant, chief of the chemical service of battalion.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] His name had to do with the beginning of developing pH-metry and ionometry, the creation and organisation of measuring equipment production, widely used in medicine, chemical and nuclear industry, aerospace technology, agriculture and many other fields.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] His achievements in solving the fundamental problems of chemical thermodynamics are noteworthy.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Special mention should be made of the generalisation of the stability conditions for the Gibbs equilibrium to heterogeneous (multicomponent, multiphase) systems (1954).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] In the frame of the thermodynamic theory existing is the «Filippov-Shultz rule».
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] The first results of the study of the Mössbauer effect in iron-containing glasses are mentioned in the thesis of Mikhail Shultz.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Schulz and staff of his laboratory are of exceptional interest for interpretation of Mössbauer's spectra, where the range assessment all of possible states of iron atoms is extremely wide and difficult.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Shultz demonstrated the possibility to get a glass electrode with redox function (1964), which allowed to create a fundamentally new measuring technique, without the use of measuring precious metals, and that gave a huge economic impact.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] The industrial production of pH-meters was originated and connected with his name.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] In the 1950–1960 on the basis of representative series of glasses M.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Shultz with collaborators estimated the impact of the third component on electrode properties of alkaline-silicate glasses (practically any element of the periodical system of D.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Mendeleev, capable to be present at glass, was involved as that component).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] According to the concept of glass developed by M.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Large enough the contribution of the scientist is in the sphere of developing new construction materials.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] In 1981 Shultz published paper on the optical fiber made out of pure cristobalite and silicone shell.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Shultz is the founder of one of Russian scientific schools.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Under his leadership 45 people maintained candidate theses, 8 people of his school became Doctors of Sciences, members of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Shultz was the president of the 15th International Congress on Glass held in Leningrad.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] It is his merit that in 1979 Russia was admitted to the most authoritative organisation of that profile—International Commission on Glass, founded in 1933.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] He was a president of the Russian Ceramic Society (1995–2002).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Member of numerous scientific state and international commissions and committees, scientific societies.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/mikhail-shultz] Member of editor's boards of several Russian and foreign scientific journals.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] Semyonov was born in Saratov in April 1896, the son of Yelena Dmitrieva and Nikolai Aleksandrovich Semyonov.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] He graduated from the department of physics of Petrograd University (1913–1917), where he was a student of Abram Fyodorovich Ioffe.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] After graduating from Saint Petersburg State University, Semyonov worked as an assistant and lecturer in Tomsk at the Tomsk University Institute of Technology, where he published his first research paper in 1916.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] In 1918, he moved to Samara, where he was enlisted into Kolchak's White Army in 1919 during the Russian Civil War, although he obtained a teaching deferment and managed to avoid service.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] In December of that same year, he was pressed into the radio service of the Red Army.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] After his discharge in the winter of 1920, Semyonov obtained work at universities in Perm and Tomsk.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] After the war, Semyonov returned to Petrograd and took charge of the electron phenomena laboratory of the Petrograd Physico-Technical Institute, continuing to occasionally travel back to Tomsk as well as at times meeting with officials from Moscow.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] He also became the vice-director of the institute.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] In 1921, he married philologist Maria Boreishe-Liverovsky (student of Zhirmunsky).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] On September 15, 1924, Nikolay married Maria's niece, Natalia Nikolayevna Burtseva.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] They had two children, son Yuri and daughter Lyudmila.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] During that difficult time, Semyonov, together with Pyotr Kapitsa, discovered a way to measure the magnetic field of an atomic nucleus (1922).
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] Later the experimental setup was improved by Otto Stern and Walther Gerlach and became known as Stern–Gerlach experiment.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] In 1925, Semyonov, together with Yakov Frenkel, studied kinetics of condensation and adsorption of vapors.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] In 1927, he studied ionisation in gases and published an important book, *Chemistry of the Electron*.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] In 1928, he, together with Vladimir Fock, created a theory of thermal disruptive discharge of dielectrics.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] In 1927, Semyonov studied the ionization of gases, the chemistry of the electron.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] In 1928, he created the theory of the broken discharge of dielectrics with Vladimir Fock.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] He lectured at the Petrograd Polytechnical Institute and was appointed Professor in 1928.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] In 1931, he organized the Institute of Physical Chemistry of the USSR Academy of Sciences (which moved to Chernogolovka in 1943) and became its first director.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] In 1932, he became a full member of the Soviet Academy of Sciences.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] The ideas of Semyonov have been applied in the science of reaction and production of polymerization reactions.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] His ideas are also applied in catalysis studies in biological systems.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] Semyonov married Natalya Nikolayevna Semyonov and together they both have a son and a daughter.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] Semyonov died on September 25, 1986, in Moscow, and was buried at the Novodevichy Cemetery.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] Semyonov's outstanding work on the mechanism of chemical transformation includes an exhaustive analysis of the application of the chain theory to varied reactions (1934–1954) and, more significantly, to combustion processes.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] He proposed a theory of degenerate branching, which led to a better understanding of the phenomena associated with the induction periods of oxidation processes.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] He spent most of his career focusing and developing the field of chemical chain reactions.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] Semyonov wrote two important books outlining his work.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] *Chemical Kinetics and Chain Reactions* was published in 1934, with an English edition in 1935.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] It was the first book in the U.S.S.R. to develop a detailed theory of unbranched and branched chain reactions in chemistry.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] *Some Problems of Chemical Kinetics and Reactivity*, first published in 1954, was revised in 1958; there are also English, American, German, and Chinese editions.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] He is the only Soviet/Russian Chemistry Nobel Laureate, who received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry (together with Sir Cyril N.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] Semyonov had long been a supporter of the Communist Party and the Soviet Union.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] After the Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists accused the Soviet Union of heavy scientific censorship in 1953, he coauthored the Soviet response which denied all accusations.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] He is also noted as being the most famous signatory to a 1971 public letter from Soviet scientists to United States president Richard Nixon, on displeasure in the murder trial of Angela Davis.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] Semyonov trained Russian organometallic chemist Alexander Shilov, who discovered platinum catalyzed C-H activation.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/nikolay-semyonov] Semyonov was also an Honorary Doctor of several universities: Oxford (1960), Brussels (1962), London (1965), Budapest Technical University (1965), Polytechnic Institute of Milan (1964) and others.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry] The **Faculty of Chemistry (since 2014 The Institute of Chemistry)** at Saint Petersburg State University is one of the leading chemistry faculties in Russia.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry] Formally, the Department of Chemistry has been created as a separate entity of Saint Petersburg State University (then Leningrad State University) in 1929.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry] However, the history of chemistry at Saint Petersburg State University began much earlier.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry] First chemistry laboratory and lectures in chemistry were introduced at the university in 1833.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry] Many Russian chemists began their career and/or worked there.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry] Among them are Nikolay Zinin, Alexey Favorsky, Lev Aleksandrovich Chugaev, Sergei Vasiljevich Lebedev, Vyacheslav Tishchenko, Vladimir Ipatieff, Nikolay Semyonov, Boris Nikolsky, Mikhail Shultz.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry] Historically, some of the first chemistry offices were located in the main building of Saint Petersburg State University called Twelve Collegia.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry] The remainder of these is the Mendeleev museum located on the first floor of the central part of this enormous building.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry] In the 20th century, the Department of Chemistry was headquartered at 41/43 Sredniy prospekt on Vasilievsky Island, about one mile west of Twelve Collegia.
[src:saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry/saint-petersburg-state-university-institute-of-chemistry] In the 1980s, most of the laboratories were relocated to a more spacious building in the newly constructed campus in the suburb of Peterhof.
